rats]]\n[[Category:People from Shumyachsky District]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People with HIV/AIDS]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:Science Fiction Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:SFWA Grand Masters]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:World federalists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-speaking people]]\n[[Category:Boys High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n[[Category:Pulp fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers about religion and science\u200e]]\n", "name_user": "79.114.120.192", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOverview)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Asimov"}
{"title_page": "Augustus G. Paine Jr.", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{infobox person\n| birth_name   = Augustus Gibson Paine Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1866|10|19}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{dda|1947|10|23|1866|10|19}}\n| death_place  = New York City, New York, U.S.\n| education    =\n| parents      = [[Augustus G. Paine Sr.]]<br>Charlotte M. Bedell Paine\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Maud Eustis Potts<br>|1888|June 4, 1919|reason=her death}}<br>{{marriage|Francisca Machado Warren<br>|1923|October 23, 1947|reason=his death}}\n| children     = 6\n| relations    = [[George Eustis Paine]] (grandson)<br>[[Molly McGreevey]] (granddaughter)\n}}\n'''Augustus Gibson Paine Jr.''' (October 19, 1866 \u2013 October 23, 1947) was an American paper manufacturer and bank official.<ref name=obituary>{{cite news |title=Augustus G. Paine |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date= October 24, 1947 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1947/10/24/archives/augustus-g-paine.html?sq=obituary+augustus+g.+paine&scp=1&st=p |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPaine was born in [[New York City]] on October 19, 1866. He was a son of [[Augustus G. Paine Sr.]] (1839\u20131915)<ref name=\"AGPObit1915\">{{cite news |title=AUGUSTUS G. PAINE DEAD.; Financier Expires at the Hotel Plaza, in His 77th Year. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1915/03/27/archives/augustus-g-paine-dead-financier-expires-at-the-hotel-plaza-in-his.html?searchResultPosition=4 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 March 1915}}</ref> and Charlotte M. ([[n\u00e9e]] Bedell) Paine (1840\u20131929).<ref>{{cite news |title=Died |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/01/16/archives/obituary-8-no-title.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=16 January 1929}}</ref>  He was educated privately in the United States and Europe.<ref name=obituary />\n\n==Career==\nIn 1885, Paine moved to [[Willsboro, New York]] to manage a local pulp mill.  He became president of the New York and Pennsylvania Company of [[Lock Haven, Pennsylvania]], which was founded in 1890.<ref name=\"psu\">{{cite web |title=New York and Pennsylvania Company Ledgers and Employment Records (Pa.), 1890-1964 HCLA 6031 |url=https://libraries.psu.edu/findingaids/6031.htm |website=libraries.psu.edu |publisher=[[Pennsylvania State University|Historical Collections and Labor Archives, Special Collections Library, Pennsylvania State University]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The firm was later based at 230 [[Park Avenue (Manhattan)|Park Avenue]]<ref name=obituary /> operated a Clarion paper mill and related industries in [[Johnsonburg, Pennsylvania]], and in 1920 built the Castanea Paper Company in Lock Haven.<ref name=\"psu\"/>  The New York and Pennsylvania Company became one of the leading paper manufacturers in the country and a major supplier to the [[Curtis Publishing Company]], the publisher of the ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]'',  ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'' and others.<ref name=obituary />\n\nIn 1945, [[Curtis Publishing Company]] acquired a 30% interest in the New York and Pennsylvania Company.<ref name=\"1945Acquisition\">{{cite news |title=TO BUY INTO PAPER PLANT; Curtis to Get 30% Interest in New York & Pennsylvania Unit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/11/10/archives/to-buy-into-paper-plant-curtis-to-get-30-interest-in-new-york.html?searchResultPosition=8 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 10, 1945}}</ref> After his death in 1947, Curtis became the sole owner of the New York and Pennsylvania Co. around 1950.<ref name=\"psu\"/>\n\n=== Ornithology ===\nPaine was an avid hobby [[ornithologist]]. At the age of 19 or 20, together with Lewis B. Woodruff, he composed a list of birds of [[Central Park]], counting over 100 species. This was regarded as the first official list of birds of [[Central Park]], and was published in ''[[Forest and Stream]]'' on June 10, 1886.<ref>{{cite journal |date=June 10, 1886 |title=List of birds of Central Park |journal=Forest and Stream |volume=XXVI |issue=20 |pages=386\u2013387 |at= |publisher=The Forest and Stream Publishing Company |location=New York}}</ref> An article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' on August 26, 1974, calls attention to this early list.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Eugene Kinkead |date=August 26, 1974 |title=The Birds of Central Park |journal=The New Yorker |volume=XXVI |issue=20 |page=78 |at= |publisher= |location=New York |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/1974/08/26/1974_08_26_078_TNY_CARDS_000310343#ixzz14RUiiUAl }}</ref>\n\nHis collection of some 1,200 specimens were later donated by his family to the [[American Museum of Natural History]] under the name \"Augustus Paine and Alvah Jordan collection of birds\". A copy of the original catalogue and documents relating to the gift were also given by the family to the museum archive.<ref name=\"amnh\">{{cite web |title=Collection: Augustus Paine and Alvah Jordan collection of birds {{!}} Research Library {{!}} Archives |url=http://data.library.amnh.org/archives/repositories/6/resources/9259 |website=data.library.amnh.org |publisher=[[American Museum of Natural History]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Austrian Consulate NYC 012.JPG|thumb|upright|The Augustus G. Paine Jr. House (the Austrian Consulate General in New York since the 1950s).]][[File:Paine Memorial Library 001.JPG|thumb|right|The Paine Memorial Library in Willsboro.]][[File:Woodlawn Cemetery Bronx 006.jpg|thumb|Graves of Augustus G. Paine Jr. and his second wife Francisca Warren in Woodlawn Cemetery, the Bronx]]\nIn 1888, he married Maud Eustis Potts (1865\u20131919),<ref name=obituary /> who converted from the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] to [[Catholicism]] in 1913.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. A.H. Paine, Jr., a Catholic Today; Leaves Her Communion with St. Mary the Virgin, Episcopal |newspaper=New York Times |date=April 11, 1913 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1913/04/11/archives/mrs-ah-paine-jr-a-catholic-today-leaves-her-communion-with-st-mary.html?sq=A.H.+Paine+Jr.&scp=1&st=p |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Maud was a daughter of George Potts and Mary Laurette (n\u00e9e Eustis) Potts. Together they were the parents of five sons, all of whom married and had children themselves:<ref name=obituary /><ref name=\"SC1956\">{{cite book |title=Supreme Court of the State of New York |date=1956 |publisher=[[Supreme Court of the State of New York]] |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tB9F1C1nM5IC&pg=RA5-PA45&lpg=RA5-PA45 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* Augustus Gibson Paine III (1891\u20131938), who married Dorothy Marian Quimby (1893\u20131937), a daughter of Dr. Charles Elihu Quimby.<ref name=\"ACCA1922\">{{cite book |title=Transactions of the American Climatological and Clinical Association |date=1922 |publisher=American Climatological and Clinical Association. |page=20 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vKVIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR20&lpg=PR20 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* George Eustis Paine (1894\u20131953),<ref name=\"GUPObit1953\">{{cite news|title=G. Eustis Paine, 59, An Industrialist {{!}} Board Chairman and Former President of Paper Concern Dies at His Home Here|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9806E5D81F3AE23BBC4051DFB5668388649EDE|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 March 1953}}</ref> was chairman of the board of the New York and Pennsylvania Co. until his death. He married Helen Ellis (1895\u20131948). After her death, he married Katryna Ten Broeck Weed (1897\u20131962), a daughter of [[New York State Assembly]]man [[George S. Weed]], in 1950.\n* Alexander Brooks Paine (1898\u20131976), who married Walburga Kaul Reilly (1902\u20131942) in 1922.<ref name=\"1922Wedding\">{{cite news |title=MISS REILLY A BRIDE: Philadelphia Girl Weds Alexander Brooks Paine of New York |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/04/02/archives/marriage-announcement-1-no-title.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 April 1922}}</ref> They later divorced before her remarriage and eventual suicide.<ref name=\"1942Suicide\">{{cite news |last1=TIMES |first1=Special to THE NEW YORK |title=MRS. STACKPOLE A SUICIDE; Plunges to Death From Room of Mother in Philadelphia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1942/10/31/archives/mrs-stackpole-a-suicide-plunges-to-death-from-room-of-mother-in.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 October 1942}}</ref>\n* Hugh Eustis Paine (1905\u20131973),<ref name=\"HOObit1973\">{{cite news |title=Hugh Paine, 68, Dies; a Stockbroker Here |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/03/31/archives/hugh-paine-68dies-a-stockbroker-here.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 31, 1973}}</ref> who married Helen Clirehugh Duncan (1906\u20131992)<ref>{{Citation|date=March 31, 1973 |title=Hugh Paine, 68, dies |periodical= [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> in 1928.<ref name=\"1928Engagement\">{{cite news |title=LEILA FLEISCHMANN ENGAGED TO MARRY; Daughter of Charles Russell Fleischmann Betrothed to John Burton Fiery. BRIDAL SET FOR OCTOBER Helen Clirehugh Duncan Affianced to Hugh Eustis Paine--Will Be Wed In the Autumn. Duncan--Paine. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/06/20/archives/leila-fleischmann-engaged-to-marry-daughter-of-charles-russell.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 June 1928}}</ref><ref name=\"1928Wedding\">{{cite news |title=MISS DUNCAN WEDS HUGH EUSTIS PAINE; Ceremony in Ballroom of the Park Lane Performed by the Rev. H.L.Sargent. Barkin--Smith. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/11/28/archives/miss-duncan-weds-hugh-eustis-paine-ceremony-in-ballroom-of-the-park.html?searchResultPosition=3 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 28, 1928}}</ref>\n* Peter Standish Paine, who was president of the New York and Pennsylvania Company. He was also CEO of the [[Great Northern Nekoosa Corporation]]. He married Ellen Cadeen Lea, a daughter of Robert C. Lea of [[Chestnut Hill, Philadelphia|Chestnut Hill]], in 1933.<ref name=\"1933Engagement\">{{cite news |title=MISS LEA TO WED SEPT. 27. Fiancee of Peter Standish Paine Chooses Her Attendants. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/09/06/archives/miss-lea-to-wed-sept-27-fiancee-of-peter-standish-paine-chooses-her.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 6, 1933}}</ref>\n\nFour years after the death of his first wife on June 4, 1919, he married Francisca Machado Warren (1891\u20131981) at St. John's Memorial Chapel in Cambridge.<ref name=\"1923Wedding\">{{cite news |title=A. G. PAINE JR. MARRIES. Union Club Member Weds Miss Francesca Warren in Cambridge. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1923/02/06/archives/a-g-paine-jr-marries-union-club-member-weds-miss-francesca-warren.html?searchResultPosition=5 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 6, 1923}}</ref> Francisca daughter of the late Minton Warren, a Latin professor at [[Johns Hopkins University|Johns Hopkins]] and later [[Harvard University]], and Salom\u00e9 (n\u00e9e Machado) Warren, who was of Cuban descent.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=John William Leonard |encyclopedia=Woman's Who's Who of America |title=WARREN, Salom\u00e9 Machado |edition= |date= |publisher=The American Commonwealth Company |location=New York |id= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |page=851 |quote=(Mrs. Minton Warren), 105 Irving St., Boston, Mass. Born Puerto Principe, Island of Cuba; dau. Juan Francisco and Elizabeth Frances (Jones) Machado; grad. Smith Coll., A.B. '83; m. Salem, Mass., Dec. 29, 1885, Prof. Minton Warren, then Latin prof. of Johns Hopkins Univ., later of Harvard Univ. (died 1907); children: Minton Machado, Francisco (''sic'') Machado. Interested in higher education of women, music, and Romance languages. Mem. Circolo Italiano of Boston. Favors woman suffrage. |ref= }}</ref> Together Francisca and Augustus were the parents of one daughter:\n\n* Francisca Warren Paine (1928\u20132016), who married David Irwin.<ref name=\"hamiltonfuneralhome\">{{cite web |title=Obituary of Francisca Irwin Paine |url=https://hamiltonfuneralhome.com/tribute/details/1186/Francisca-Paine/obituary.html |website=hamiltonfuneralhome.com |publisher=Hamilton Funeral Home |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=garden />\n\nAfter a long illness, Paine died on October 23, 1947 at the age of 81 at his home, 31 [[69th Street (Manhattan)|East 69th Street]] in Manhattan.<ref name=obituary /> He was buried at [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]] in the [[Bronx]]. His widow lived another three decades until her death on February 8, 1981.\n\n===Descendants===\nThrough his second son George, he was a grandfather of [[New York State Senate|New York State Senator]] [[George Eustis Paine]] (1920\u20131991) who married, and divorced, Joan Widener Leidy, a granddaughter of art collector [[Joseph E. Widener]].<ref name=\"1941Engagement\">{{cite news|title=MISS JOAN LEIDY ENGAGED TO WED; Troth of Joseph E. Widener's Granddaughter to Geo. Paine Jr. Announced in Florida SHE IS OGONTZ STUDENT Graduate of Fermata School in Aiken, S. C. -- Fiance Attended Princeton|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1941/04/12/archives/misg-joan-leidy-engaged-to-ed-troth-of-joseph-e-wideners.html|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 April 1941}}</ref> He was also a grandfather of Augustus Gibson Paine II (1919\u20131993),<ref name=\"AGO2Obit1993\">{{cite news |title=Augustus G. Paine 2d, A Paper Executive, 73 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/10/obituaries/augustus-g-paine-2d-a-paper-executive-73.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 May 1993}}</ref> who was married (and divorced) Iris Vanderbilt Smith (1927\u20132006), a daughter of [[Earl E. T. Smith]], the former [[U.S. Ambassador to Cuba]] and granddaughter of [[Virginia Fair Vanderbilt]] and [[William Kissam Vanderbilt II]].<ref name=\"1976Wedding\">{{cite news |title=Jonathan Keith to Wed Helen E. Paine in Fall |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/04/18/archives/jonathan-keith-to-wed-helen-e-paine-in-fall.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 April 1976}}</ref> Augustus also served as president of New York and Pennsylvania Co. before becoming a partner in the Wall Street firm of [[E. W. Clark & Co.|Clark, Dodge & Company]] from 1963 until retiring in 1973.<ref name=\"AGO2Obit1993\"/>\n\nThrough his son Hugh, he was also a grandfather of the actress [[Molly McGreevey]] (1936\u20132015), formerly Mary Wheaton Paine, known for her role as [[Polly Longworth]] on the daytime [[television]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Ryan's Hope]]''.<ref name=\"Molly2015\">{{cite news |title=McGREEVY--Molly Paine |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=176376735 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThrough his son Peter, he was a grandfather of Peter Standish Paine Jr. (d. 2004), a 1932 graduate of [[Princeton University]] who became president of New York and Pennsylvania Co. in 1945 and a partner in the law firm of [[Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton]].  Paine also served as trustee and president of the [[Museum of the City of New York]].<ref name=\"princeton\">{{cite web |title=Memorial Peter Standish Paine \u201932 |url=https://paw.princeton.edu/memorial/peter-standish-paine-%E2%80%9932 |website=paw.princeton.edu |publisher=[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"1989Wedding\">{{cite news |title=Els M. Neukermans to Wed in August |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/31/style/els-m-neukermans-to-wed-in-august.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 December 1989}}</ref>\n\n=== Residences ===\n{{See|Flat Rock Camp}}\nPaine was closely associated with the architect [[C. P. H. Gilbert]], who received a number of commissions from him, such as his townhouse in New York's Upper East Side on 31 East 69th Street in 1917\u201318.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Doane |first=Ralph Harrington|title=The Residence of Augustus G. Paine, Esq. |journal=The Architectural Review |volume=VIII |issue= 5 |date=May 1919 |pages=123\u2013126| publisher=The Architectural Review, Inc. |location=New York}}</ref> The house was sold to the [[Austrian government]] in 1952, the Austrian Consulate General is located in it today.<ref>{{cite news |title=Austria Acquires Residence in City; Buys Clendenin Ryan's Home in New Foreign Service Area for Consulate General |newspaper=New York Times |date= February 24, 1952 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/02/24/archives/austria-acquires-residence-1n-city-buys-clendenin-ryans-home-in-new.html?sq=austrian+consulate+general+paine&scp=1&st=p |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Streetscapes: 40 East 70th Street; A Growth Plan for a Neo-Georgian Garage |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 26, 1992 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/26/realestate/streetscapes-40-east-70th-street-a-growth-plan-for-a-neo-georgian-garage.html?scp=1&sq=christopher+gray+40+east+70th+street+plans+garage&st=nyt |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bmeia.gv.at/en/embassy/consulate-general-new-york/consulate-general.html |title=Austrian Consulate General |author= |year=2010 |work= |publisher=Federal Ministry for European and International Affairs |accessdate=November 1, 2010}}</ref> When Paine was based in Willsboro, Gilbert also received commissions from him to construct the [[Essex County, New York|Essex County]] Bank in 1921.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aarch.org/events/handouts/willsboro.pdf |title=Architecture of the Champlain Valley, Willsboro |year=2010 |publisher=Adirondack Architectural Heritage |accessdate=November 1, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101025083438/http://aarch.org/events/handouts/willsboro.pdf| archivedate= October 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In May 1930, Paine donated $150,000 for a library to the town of Willsboro in memory of his mother.<ref name=\"1930Gift\">{{cite news |title=$150,000 GIFT FOR LIBRARY.; A.G. Paine Provides Memorial for Mother at Willsboro, N.Y. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/05/20/archives/150000-gift-for-library-ag-paine-provides-memorial-for-mother-at.html?searchResultPosition=15 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 20, 1930}}</ref> Both the bank and the library were constructed by Gilbert in the Neoclassical style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.willsborony.com/painememoriallibrary/my%20site%20one/History2.htm |title=History |author= |year=2010 |publisher=Paine Memorial Library |accessdate=November 14, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1885, after moving to Willsboro, Paine began buying land in the area, eventually amassing about {{convert|1000|acre}}, including three miles of [[Lake Champlain]] shoreline.<ref name=\"garden\">{{cite book |last1=Loughrey |first1=Janet |title=Gardens Adirondack Style |date=2005 |publisher=Down East Enterprises |isbn=0-89272-623-7 |pages=137-140 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=San24dYk92oC&lpg=PA140 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>  There he built his [[Flat Rock Camp]] compound,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aarch.org/resources/map/county/essex/window/flat.html |title=Flat Rock Camp |year=2010 |publisher=Adirondack Architectural Heritage |accessdate=November 1, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101025122610/http://aarch.org/resources/map/county/essex/window/flat.html| archivedate= October 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> which featured extensive gardens, planted on [[topsoil]] laid over the [[sandstone]], which were maintained under the guidance of his first wife, Maud, and, after her death, his second wife Francisca and their daughter.  The gardens are listed in the [[Smithsonian]] Archives of American Gardens.<ref name=garden />  The camp and its surrounding property, which includes [[wetland]]s, farmland, orchards and forests, are still owned by the Paine family, but in 1978 they were placed under the stewardship of the [[The Nature Conservancy|Adirondack Nature Conservancy]] to ensure that the land will not be developed in the future.<ref name=garden />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons}}\n*{{findagrave|7376373|Augustus Gibson Paine, Jr}}\n\n{{#related:Molly McGreevey}}\n{{#related:Willsboro, New York}}\n{{#related:Augustus G. Paine Sr.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paine, Augustus G. Jr.}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:American bankers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Willsboro, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{infobox person\n| birth_name   = Augustus Gibson Paine Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1866|10|19}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{dda|1947|10|23|1866|10|19}}\n| death_place  = New York City, New York, U.S.\n| education    =\n| parents      = [[Augustus G. Paine Sr.]]<br>Charlotte M. Bedell Paine\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Maud Eustis Potts<br>|1888|June 4, 1919|reason=her death}}<br>{{marriage|Francisca Machado Warren<br>|1923|October 23, 1947|reason=his death}}\n| children     = 6\n| relations    = [[George Eustis Paine]] (grandson)<br>[[Molly McGreevey]] (granddaughter)\n}}\n'''Augustus Gibson Paine Jr.''' (October 19, 1866 \u2013 October 23, 1947) was an American paper manufacturer and bank official.<ref name=obituary>{{cite news |title=Augustus G. Paine |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date= October 24, 1947 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1947/10/24/archives/augustus-g-paine.html?sq=obituary+augustus+g.+paine&scp=1&st=p |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPaine was born in [[New York City]] on October 19, 1866. He was a son of [[Augustus G. Paine Sr.]] (1839\u20131915)<ref name=\"AGPObit1915\">{{cite news |title=AUGUSTUS G. PAINE DEAD.; Financier Expires at the Hotel Plaza, in His 77th Year. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1915/03/27/archives/augustus-g-paine-dead-financier-expires-at-the-hotel-plaza-in-his.html?searchResultPosition=4 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 March 1915}}</ref> and Charlotte M. ([[n\u00e9e]] Bedell) Paine (1840\u20131929).<ref>{{cite news |title=Died |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/01/16/archives/obituary-8-no-title.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=16 January 1929}}</ref>  He was educated privately in the United States and Europe.<ref name=obituary />\n\n==Career==\nIn 1885, Paine moved to [[Willsboro, New York]] to manage a local pulp mill.  He became president of the New York and Pennsylvania Company of [[Lock Haven, Pennsylvania]], which was founded in 1890.<ref name=\"psu\">{{cite web |title=New York and Pennsylvania Company Ledgers and Employment Records (Pa.), 1890-1964 HCLA 6031 |url=https://libraries.psu.edu/findingaids/6031.htm |website=libraries.psu.edu |publisher=[[Pennsylvania State University|Historical Collections and Labor Archives, Special Collections Library, Pennsylvania State University]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The firm was later based at 230 [[Park Avenue (Manhattan)|Park Avenue]]<ref name=obituary /> operated a Clarion paper mill and related industries in [[Johnsonburg, Pennsylvania]], and in 1920 built the Castanea Paper Company in Lock Haven.<ref name=\"psu\"/>  The New York and Pennsylvania Company became one of the leading paper manufacturers in the country and a major supplier to the [[Curtis Publishing Company]], the publisher of the ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]'',  ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'' and others.<ref name=obituary />\n\nIn 1945, [[Curtis Publishing Company]] acquired a 30% interest in the the New York and Pennsylvania Company.<ref name=\"1945Acquisition\">{{cite news |title=TO BUY INTO PAPER PLANT; Curtis to Get 30% Interest in New York & Pennsylvania Unit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/11/10/archives/to-buy-into-paper-plant-curtis-to-get-30-interest-in-new-york.html?searchResultPosition=8 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 10, 1945}}</ref> After his death in 1947, Curtis became the sole owner of the New York and Pennsylvania Co. around 1950.<ref name=\"psu\"/>\n\n=== Ornithology ===\nPaine was an avid hobby [[ornithologist]]. At the age of 19 or 20, together with Lewis B. Woodruff, he composed a list of birds of [[Central Park]], counting over 100 species. This was regarded as the first official list of birds of [[Central Park]], and was published in ''[[Forest and Stream]]'' on June 10, 1886.<ref>{{cite journal |date=June 10, 1886 |title=List of birds of Central Park |journal=Forest and Stream |volume=XXVI |issue=20 |pages=386\u2013387 |at= |publisher=The Forest and Stream Publishing Company |location=New York}}</ref> An article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' on August 26, 1974, calls attention to this early list.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Eugene Kinkead |date=August 26, 1974 |title=The Birds of Central Park |journal=The New Yorker |volume=XXVI |issue=20 |page=78 |at= |publisher= |location=New York |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/1974/08/26/1974_08_26_078_TNY_CARDS_000310343#ixzz14RUiiUAl }}</ref>\n\nHis collection of some 1,200 specimens were later donated by his family to the [[American Museum of Natural History]] under the name \"Augustus Paine and Alvah Jordan collection of birds\". A copy of the original catalogue and documents relating to the gift were also given by the family to the museum archive.<ref name=\"amnh\">{{cite web |title=Collection: Augustus Paine and Alvah Jordan collection of birds {{!}} Research Library {{!}} Archives |url=http://data.library.amnh.org/archives/repositories/6/resources/9259 |website=data.library.amnh.org |publisher=[[American Museum of Natural History]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Austrian Consulate NYC 012.JPG|thumb|upright|The Augustus G. Paine Jr. House (the Austrian Consulate General in New York since the 1950s).]][[File:Paine Memorial Library 001.JPG|thumb|right|The Paine Memorial Library in Willsboro.]][[File:Woodlawn Cemetery Bronx 006.jpg|thumb|Graves of Augustus G. Paine Jr. and his second wife Francisca Warren in Woodlawn Cemetery, the Bronx]]\nIn 1888, he married Maud Eustis Potts (1865\u20131919),<ref name=obituary /> who converted from the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] to [[Catholicism]] in 1913.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. A.H. Paine, Jr., a Catholic Today; Leaves Her Communion with St. Mary the Virgin, Episcopal |newspaper=New York Times |date=April 11, 1913 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1913/04/11/archives/mrs-ah-paine-jr-a-catholic-today-leaves-her-communion-with-st-mary.html?sq=A.H.+Paine+Jr.&scp=1&st=p |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Maud was a daughter of George Potts and Mary Laurette (n\u00e9e Eustis) Potts. Together they were the parents of five sons, all of whom married and had children themselves:<ref name=obituary /><ref name=\"SC1956\">{{cite book |title=Supreme Court of the State of New York |date=1956 |publisher=[[Supreme Court of the State of New York]] |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tB9F1C1nM5IC&pg=RA5-PA45&lpg=RA5-PA45 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* Augustus Gibson Paine III (1891\u20131938), who married Dorothy Marian Quimby (1893\u20131937), a daughter of Dr. Charles Elihu Quimby.<ref name=\"ACCA1922\">{{cite book |title=Transactions of the American Climatological and Clinical Association |date=1922 |publisher=American Climatological and Clinical Association. |page=20 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vKVIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR20&lpg=PR20 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* George Eustis Paine (1894\u20131953),<ref name=\"GUPObit1953\">{{cite news|title=G. Eustis Paine, 59, An Industrialist {{!}} Board Chairman and Former President of Paper Concern Dies at His Home Here|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9806E5D81F3AE23BBC4051DFB5668388649EDE|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 March 1953}}</ref> was chairman of the board of the New York and Pennsylvania Co. until his death. He married Helen Ellis (1895\u20131948). After her death, he married Katryna Ten Broeck Weed (1897\u20131962), a daughter of [[New York State Assembly]]man [[George S. Weed]], in 1950.\n* Alexander Brooks Paine (1898\u20131976), who married Walburga Kaul Reilly (1902\u20131942) in 1922.<ref name=\"1922Wedding\">{{cite news |title=MISS REILLY A BRIDE: Philadelphia Girl Weds Alexander Brooks Paine of New York |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/04/02/archives/marriage-announcement-1-no-title.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 April 1922}}</ref> They later divorced before her remarriage and eventual suicide.<ref name=\"1942Suicide\">{{cite news |last1=TIMES |first1=Special to THE NEW YORK |title=MRS. STACKPOLE A SUICIDE; Plunges to Death From Room of Mother in Philadelphia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1942/10/31/archives/mrs-stackpole-a-suicide-plunges-to-death-from-room-of-mother-in.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 October 1942}}</ref>\n* Hugh Eustis Paine (1905\u20131973),<ref name=\"HOObit1973\">{{cite news |title=Hugh Paine, 68, Dies; a Stockbroker Here |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/03/31/archives/hugh-paine-68dies-a-stockbroker-here.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 31, 1973}}</ref> who married Helen Clirehugh Duncan (1906\u20131992)<ref>{{Citation|date=March 31, 1973 |title=Hugh Paine, 68, dies |periodical= [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> in 1928.<ref name=\"1928Engagement\">{{cite news |title=LEILA FLEISCHMANN ENGAGED TO MARRY; Daughter of Charles Russell Fleischmann Betrothed to John Burton Fiery. BRIDAL SET FOR OCTOBER Helen Clirehugh Duncan Affianced to Hugh Eustis Paine--Will Be Wed In the Autumn. Duncan--Paine. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/06/20/archives/leila-fleischmann-engaged-to-marry-daughter-of-charles-russell.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 June 1928}}</ref><ref name=\"1928Wedding\">{{cite news |title=MISS DUNCAN WEDS HUGH EUSTIS PAINE; Ceremony in Ballroom of the Park Lane Performed by the Rev. H.L.Sargent. Barkin--Smith. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/11/28/archives/miss-duncan-weds-hugh-eustis-paine-ceremony-in-ballroom-of-the-park.html?searchResultPosition=3 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 28, 1928}}</ref>\n* Peter Standish Paine, who was president of the New York and Pennsylvania Company. He was also CEO of the [[Great Northern Nekoosa Corporation]]. He married Ellen Cadeen Lea, a daughter of Robert C. Lea of [[Chestnut Hill, Philadelphia|Chestnut Hill]], in 1933.<ref name=\"1933Engagement\">{{cite news |title=MISS LEA TO WED SEPT. 27. Fiancee of Peter Standish Paine Chooses Her Attendants. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/09/06/archives/miss-lea-to-wed-sept-27-fiancee-of-peter-standish-paine-chooses-her.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 6, 1933}}</ref>\n\nFour years after the death of his first wife on June 4, 1919, he married Francisca Machado Warren (1891\u20131981) at St. John's Memorial Chapel in Cambridge.<ref name=\"1923Wedding\">{{cite news |title=A. G. PAINE JR. MARRIES. Union Club Member Weds Miss Francesca Warren in Cambridge. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1923/02/06/archives/a-g-paine-jr-marries-union-club-member-weds-miss-francesca-warren.html?searchResultPosition=5 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 6, 1923}}</ref> Francisca daughter of the late Minton Warren, a Latin professor at [[Johns Hopkins University|Johns Hopkins]] and later [[Harvard University]], and Salom\u00e9 (n\u00e9e Machado) Warren, who was of Cuban descent.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=John William Leonard |encyclopedia=Woman's Who's Who of America |title=WARREN, Salom\u00e9 Machado |edition= |date= |publisher=The American Commonwealth Company |location=New York |id= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |page=851 |quote=(Mrs. Minton Warren), 105 Irving St., Boston, Mass. Born Puerto Principe, Island of Cuba; dau. Juan Francisco and Elizabeth Frances (Jones) Machado; grad. Smith Coll., A.B. '83; m. Salem, Mass., Dec. 29, 1885, Prof. Minton Warren, then Latin prof. of Johns Hopkins Univ., later of Harvard Univ. (died 1907); children: Minton Machado, Francisco (''sic'') Machado. Interested in higher education of women, music, and Romance languages. Mem. Circolo Italiano of Boston. Favors woman suffrage. |ref= }}</ref> Together Francisca and Augustus were the parents of one daughter:\n\n* Francisca Warren Paine (1928\u20132016), who married David Irwin.<ref name=\"hamiltonfuneralhome\">{{cite web |title=Obituary of Francisca Irwin Paine |url=https://hamiltonfuneralhome.com/tribute/details/1186/Francisca-Paine/obituary.html |website=hamiltonfuneralhome.com |publisher=Hamilton Funeral Home |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=garden />\n\nAfter a long illness, Paine died on October 23, 1947 at the age of 81 at his home, 31 [[69th Street (Manhattan)|East 69th Street]] in Manhattan.<ref name=obituary /> He was buried at [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]] in the [[Bronx]]. His widow lived another three decades until her death on February 8, 1981.\n\n===Descendants===\nThrough his second son George, he was a grandfather of [[New York State Senate|New York State Senator]] [[George Eustis Paine]] (1920\u20131991) who married, and divorced, Joan Widener Leidy, a granddaughter of art collector [[Joseph E. Widener]].<ref name=\"1941Engagement\">{{cite news|title=MISS JOAN LEIDY ENGAGED TO WED; Troth of Joseph E. Widener's Granddaughter to Geo. Paine Jr. Announced in Florida SHE IS OGONTZ STUDENT Graduate of Fermata School in Aiken, S. C. -- Fiance Attended Princeton|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1941/04/12/archives/misg-joan-leidy-engaged-to-ed-troth-of-joseph-e-wideners.html|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 April 1941}}</ref> He was also a grandfather of Augustus Gibson Paine II (1919\u20131993),<ref name=\"AGO2Obit1993\">{{cite news |title=Augustus G. Paine 2d, A Paper Executive, 73 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/10/obituaries/augustus-g-paine-2d-a-paper-executive-73.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 May 1993}}</ref> who was married (and divorced) Iris Vanderbilt Smith (1927\u20132006), a daughter of [[Earl E. T. Smith]], the former [[U.S. Ambassador to Cuba]] and granddaughter of [[Virginia Fair Vanderbilt]] and [[William Kissam Vanderbilt II]].<ref name=\"1976Wedding\">{{cite news |title=Jonathan Keith to Wed Helen E. Paine in Fall |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/04/18/archives/jonathan-keith-to-wed-helen-e-paine-in-fall.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 April 1976}}</ref> Augustus also served as president of New York and Pennsylvania Co. before becoming a partner in the Wall Street firm of [[E. W. Clark & Co.|Clark, Dodge & Company]] from 1963 until retiring in 1973.<ref name=\"AGO2Obit1993\"/>\n\nThrough his son Hugh, he was also a grandfather of the actress [[Molly McGreevey]] (1936\u20132015), formerly Mary Wheaton Paine, known for her role as [[Polly Longworth]] on the daytime [[television]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Ryan's Hope]]''.<ref name=\"Molly2015\">{{cite news |title=McGREEVY--Molly Paine |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=176376735 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThrough his son Peter, he was a grandfather of Peter Standish Paine Jr. (d. 2004), a 1932 graduate of [[Princeton University]] who became president of New York and Pennsylvania Co. in 1945 and a partner in the law firm of [[Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton]].  Paine also served as trustee and president of the [[Museum of the City of New York]].<ref name=\"princeton\">{{cite web |title=Memorial Peter Standish Paine \u201932 |url=https://paw.princeton.edu/memorial/peter-standish-paine-%E2%80%9932 |website=paw.princeton.edu |publisher=[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"1989Wedding\">{{cite news |title=Els M. Neukermans to Wed in August |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/31/style/els-m-neukermans-to-wed-in-august.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 December 1989}}</ref>\n\n=== Residences ===\n{{See|Flat Rock Camp}}\nPaine was closely associated with the architect [[C. P. H. Gilbert]], who received a number of commissions from him, such as his townhouse in New York's Upper East Side on 31 East 69th Street in 1917\u201318.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Doane |first=Ralph Harrington|title=The Residence of Augustus G. Paine, Esq. |journal=The Architectural Review |volume=VIII |issue= 5 |date=May 1919 |pages=123\u2013126| publisher=The Architectural Review, Inc. |location=New York}}</ref> The house was sold to the [[Austrian government]] in 1952, the Austrian Consulate General is located in it today.<ref>{{cite news |title=Austria Acquires Residence in City; Buys Clendenin Ryan's Home in New Foreign Service Area for Consulate General |newspaper=New York Times |date= February 24, 1952 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/02/24/archives/austria-acquires-residence-1n-city-buys-clendenin-ryans-home-in-new.html?sq=austrian+consulate+general+paine&scp=1&st=p |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Streetscapes: 40 East 70th Street; A Growth Plan for a Neo-Georgian Garage |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 26, 1992 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/26/realestate/streetscapes-40-east-70th-street-a-growth-plan-for-a-neo-georgian-garage.html?scp=1&sq=christopher+gray+40+east+70th+street+plans+garage&st=nyt |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bmeia.gv.at/en/embassy/consulate-general-new-york/consulate-general.html |title=Austrian Consulate General |author= |year=2010 |work= |publisher=Federal Ministry for European and International Affairs |accessdate=November 1, 2010}}</ref> When Paine was based in Willsboro, Gilbert also received commissions from him to construct the [[Essex County, New York|Essex County]] Bank in 1921.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aarch.org/events/handouts/willsboro.pdf |title=Architecture of the Champlain Valley, Willsboro |year=2010 |publisher=Adirondack Architectural Heritage |accessdate=November 1, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101025083438/http://aarch.org/events/handouts/willsboro.pdf| archivedate= October 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In May 1930, Paine donated $150,000 for a library to the town of Willsboro in memory of his mother.<ref name=\"1930Gift\">{{cite news |title=$150,000 GIFT FOR LIBRARY.; A.G. Paine Provides Memorial for Mother at Willsboro, N.Y. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/05/20/archives/150000-gift-for-library-ag-paine-provides-memorial-for-mother-at.html?searchResultPosition=15 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 20, 1930}}</ref> Both the bank and the library were constructed by Gilbert in the Neoclassical style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.willsborony.com/painememoriallibrary/my%20site%20one/History2.htm |title=History |author= |year=2010 |publisher=Paine Memorial Library |accessdate=November 14, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1885, after moving to Willsboro, Paine began buying land in the area, eventually amassing about {{convert|1000|acre}}, including three miles of [[Lake Champlain]] shoreline.<ref name=\"garden\">{{cite book |last1=Loughrey |first1=Janet |title=Gardens Adirondack Style |date=2005 |publisher=Down East Enterprises |isbn=0-89272-623-7 |pages=137-140 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=San24dYk92oC&lpg=PA140 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>  There he built his [[Flat Rock Camp]] compound,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aarch.org/resources/map/county/essex/window/flat.html |title=Flat Rock Camp |year=2010 |publisher=Adirondack Architectural Heritage |accessdate=November 1, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101025122610/http://aarch.org/resources/map/county/essex/window/flat.html| archivedate= October 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> which featured extensive gardens, planted on [[topsoil]] laid over the [[sandstone]], which were maintained under the guidance of his first wife, Maud, and, after her death, his second wife Francisca and their daughter.  The gardens are listed in the [[Smithsonian]] Archives of American Gardens.<ref name=garden />  The camp and its surrounding property, which includes [[wetland]]s, farmland, orchards and forests, are still owned by the Paine family, but in 1978 they were placed under the stewardship of the [[The Nature Conservancy|Adirondack Nature Conservancy]] to ensure that the land will not be developed in the future.<ref name=garden />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons}}\n*{{findagrave|7376373|Augustus Gibson Paine, Jr}}\n\n{{#related:Molly McGreevey}}\n{{#related:Willsboro, New York}}\n{{#related:Augustus G. Paine Sr.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paine, Augustus G. Jr.}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:American bankers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Willsboro, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustus_G._Paine_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Brothel", "text_new": "{{short description|Place of prostitution}}\n{{about||the 2008 film|Brothel (film)|other uses}}\n{{redirect|Whorehouse|the TV cartoon episode|Whorehouse (Beavis and Butt-Head episode)}}\n[[File:Joachim Beuckelaer - Brothel - Walters 371784.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Joachim Beuckelaer]], ''Brothel'', 1562]] \n[[Image:Pascha K\u00f6ln.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Pascha (brothel)|Pascha brothel]] in [[Cologne, Germany]], the largest brothel in Europe.<ref name=faz>[http://www.faz.net/s/RubCD175863466D41BB9A6A93D460B81174/Doc~E5CC9DBCF62BF40E4AE97BB61D42A9FA8~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html \u201eDie Welt zu Gast bei Freundinnen\u201c], ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'', 8 June 2006. {{in lang|de}}</ref> During the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], the poster had the [[Saudi Arabian flag]] and [[Iranian flag]] blacked out after protests and threats.]] \nA '''brothel''', '''bordello''', '''ranche'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/45429049/|title=Reading Times from Reading, Pennsylvania on October 8, 1883 \u00b7 Page 1|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> or '''whorehouse''' is a place where people engage in [[Human sexual activity|sexual activity]] with [[prostitute]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/brothel|title=Definition of BROTHEL|last=|first=|date=|website=www.merriam-webster.com|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> Technically, any premises where [[prostitution]] commonly takes place qualifies as a brothel.  However, for legal or cultural reasons, establishments often describe themselves as [[massage parlor]]s, [[bar (establishment)|bar]]s, [[strip club]]s, body rub parlours, studios, or by some other description. [[Sex work]] in a brothel is considered safer than [[street prostitution]].{{sfn|Carroll|2015|p=492}}\n\n=={{anchor|Current legal status}} Legal status==\nAround the world, attitudes towards prostitution and how and if it should be regulated vary considerably, and have varied over time. Part of the discussion impacts on whether the operation of brothels should be legal, and if so, to what sort of regulations they should be subjected.\n\nOn 2 December 1949, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] approved the [[Convention for the Suppression of the Traffic in Persons and of the Exploitation of the Prostitution of Others]].<ref>General Assembly resolution 317(IV)</ref> The Convention came into effect on 25 July 1951 and by December 2013 had been ratified by 82 states.<ref name=ratifications>{{cite web|url=http://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=VII-11-a&chapter=7&lang=en |title=United Nations Treaty Collection |accessdate=29 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907020434/https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=VII-11-a&chapter=7&lang=en |archivedate=7 September 2015 }}</ref> The Convention seeks to combat prostitution, which it regards as \"incompatible with the dignity and worth of the human person.\" Parties to the Convention agreed to abolish regulation of individual prostitutes, and to ban brothels and [[Procuring (prostitution)|procuring]]. Some countries not parties to the Convention also ban prostitution or the operation of brothels. Various United Nations commissions, however, have differing positions on the issue. For example, in 2012, a [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]] (UNAIDS) convened by [[Ban Ki-moon]] and backed by [[United Nations Development Programme]] and UNAIDS, recommended decriminalization of brothels and procuring.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/4128420.html Decriminalisation integral to the fight against HIV] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409071255/http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/4128420.html# |date=2014-04-09 }}, Michael Kirby & Michael Wong, Australian Broadcasting Corporation, 13 JULY 2012</ref><ref>[http://cnsnews.com/news/article/un-commission-calls-legalizing-prostitution-worldwide U.N. Commission Calls for Legalizing Prostitution Worldwide], Amanda Swysgood, CNS News, July 23, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.hivlawcommission.org/resources/report/FinalReport-Risks,Rights&Health-EN.pdf Risks, Rights & Health] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924030555/http://www.hivlawcommission.org/resources/report/FinalReport-Risks%2CRights%26Health-EN.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}, GLOBAL COMMISSION ON HIV AND THE LAW, UNDP, HIV/AIDS Group, , July 2012, page 43 (\"Recommendation\"): \"Repeal laws that prohibit consenting adults to buy or sell sex, as well as laws that otherwise prohibit commercial sex, such as laws against \"immoral\" earnings, \"living off the earnings\" of prostitution and brothel-keeping.\"</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/aug/2/aids-used-as-reason-to-legalize-prostitutes/|title=AIDS used as reason to legalize prostitutes|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|first=The Washington Times|work=The Washington Times|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Red-light district of Amsterdam by day. 2012.JPG|thumb|left|250px|[[De Wallen]], [[Amsterdam]]\u2019s [[red-light district]], offers activities such as legal [[Prostitution in the Netherlands|prostitution]] and a number of [[coffee shops]] that sell [[marijuana]]. It is one of the main tourist attractions.]]\nIn the [[European Union]], there is no uniform policy and no consensus on the issue; and laws vary widely from country to country. Netherlands and Germany have the most liberal policies; in Sweden (and in Norway and Iceland outside the EU) the buying, but not selling, of sex, is illegal; in most former Communist countries the laws target the prostitutes; while in countries such as the UK (except Northern Ireland), Italy, and Spain the act of prostitution is not itself illegal, but soliciting, pimping and brothels are, making it difficult to engage in prostitution without breaking any law. The [[European Women's Lobby]] condemns prostitution as \"an intolerable form of male violence\" and supports the \"Swedish model\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womenslobby.eu/spip.php?article472&lang=en |title=European Women's Lobby Europ\u00e9en des femmes: Prostitution in Europe: 60 Years of Reluctance |publisher=Womenslobby.eu |date= |accessdate=2013-09-03}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, the members of the European Parliament voted in a non-binding resolution, (adopted by 343 votes to 139; with 105 abstentions), in favor of the \"Swedish Model\" of criminalizing the buying, but not the selling of sex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/news-room/content/20140221IPR36644/html/Punish-the-client-not-the-prostitute|title=Punish the client, not the prostitute {{!}} News {{!}} European Parliament|website=News {{!}} European Parliament|access-date=2017-03-02|date=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Prostitution laws of the world2.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Brothels are legal only in countries and areas shown in green or light blue]]\n[[File:Trier Hafenmelodie1.jpg|thumb|250px|Brothel Hafenmelodie [[Trier]] (Germany)]]\nProstitution and the operation of brothels is illegal in many countries, though known illegal brothels may be tolerated or laws not strictly enforced. Such situations exist in many parts of the world, but the region most often associated with these policies is [[Prostitution in Asia|Asia]]. When brothels are illegal they may nevertheless operate in the guise of a legitimate business, such as massage parlors, saunas or spas.\n\nIn other places, prostitution itself may be legal, but many activities which surround it (such as operating a brothel, pimping, and soliciting in a public place) are illegal, often making it very difficult for people to engage in prostitution without breaking any law. This is the situation, for example, in the [[United Kingdom]], [[Italy]] and [[Spain]].\n\nIn a few countries, prostitution and operating a brothel is legal and regulated. The degree of regulation varies widely by country. Most of these countries allow brothels, at least in theory, as they are considered to be less problematic than [[street prostitution]]. In parts of [[Australia]], for example, brothels are legal and regulated. Regulation includes planning controls and licensing and registration requirements, and there may be other restrictions. However, the existence of licensed brothels does not stop illegal brothels from operating. According to a report in the Australian ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Telegraph]]'', illegal brothels in [[Sydney]] in 2009 outnumbered licensed operations by four to one;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/05/18/2573799.htm |title=NSW papers urged to cut brothel ads, ABC news |language=bg |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2009-05-18 |accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rideworks.com/|title=Entertainment Agency by RideWorks|last=|first=|date=|website=rideworks.com|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> while in [[Queensland]] only 10% of prostitution happens in licensed brothels, with the rest being either unregulated or illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/queensland-sex-industry-still-largely-illegitimate-20090816-embf.html |title=Queensland sex industry still largely illegitimate, Brisbane Times |publisher=Brisbanetimes.com.au |date=2009-08-16 |accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> The introduction of legal brothels in Queensland was to help improve the safety of sex workers, punters and the community at large and reduce crime. This is believed to have been successful in many ways in Queensland with The Viper Room being one of the most well known, clean, safe and most highly regard brothels in Brisbane and Queensland.<ref name=\"Prostitution Act 1999\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.legislation.qld.gov.au/view/pdf/2017-06-30/act-1999-073 |title=Prostitution Act 1999 |date=2017-06-30 |accessdate=2018-11-06 |website=Queensland Legislation\u2014Queensland Government |publisher=Office of the Queensland Parliamentary Counsel |publication-place=\nBrisbane, Queensland, Australia}}</ref>\nThe [[Netherlands]] has one of the most liberal prostitution policies in the world, and attracts sex tourists from many other countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/uruguay/10216201/A-guide-to-the-worlds-most-libertarian-countries.html|title=Uruguay and marijuana: a guide to the world's most libertarian countries|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> [[Amsterdam]] is well known for its red-light district and is a destination for [[sex tourism]]. [[Germany]] also has very liberal prostitution laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/katherine-koster/legal-in-theory-germanys-_b_8037820.html|title=Legal in Theory: Germany's Sex Trade Laws and Why They Have Nothing to Do With Amnesty Sex Work Proposal|last=Koster|first=Katherine|date=2015-08-26|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> The largest brothel in Europe is the [[Pascha (brothel)|Pascha]] in [[Cologne]]. Although the [[Dumas Brothel|Dumas Hotel]] in Butte, Montana operated legally from 1890 until 1982, brothels are currently illegal [[Prostitution in the United States|throughout the United States]], [[Prostitution in Nevada|except in rural Nevada]]; prostitution outside these licensed brothels is illegal throughout the state. All forms of prostitution are illegal in [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]], which contains the [[Las Vegas\u2013Paradise, NV MSA|Las Vegas\u2013Paradise metropolitan area]].\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of prostitution}}\n[[File:Get lautrec 1894 salon in the rue des moulins.jpg|thumb|[[Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec]], ''Salon at the Rue des Moulins'', 1894]]\nThe earliest recorded mention of prostitution as an occupation appears in Sumerian records from ca. 2400 [[Common Era|BCE]] and describes a temple-bordello operated by [[Sumerian religion|Sumerian priests]] in the city of Uruk. The 'kakum' or temple was dedicated to the goddess [[Ishtar]] and housed three grades of women. The first group performed only in the temple sex-rites; the second group had the run of the grounds and catered to its visitors as well; and the third and lowest class lived on the temple grounds but were free to seek out customers in the streets. In later years, [[sacred prostitution]] and similar classifications of females were known to have existed in Greece, Rome, India, China, and Japan.{{sfn|Murphy|1983| }}\n\n===Europe===\nState brothels/bordellos with regulated prices existed in ancient [[Athens]], created by the legendary lawmaker [[Solon]]. These brothels catered for a predominantly male clientele, with women of all ages and young men providing sexual services (see [[Prostitution in ancient Greece]]). In ancient Rome female slaves provided sexual services for soldiers, with brothels being located close to barracks and city walls. Brothels existed everywhere. The custom was to display lit candles to signal that they were open.\n\nBefore the appearance of effective [[contraception]], [[infanticide]] was common in brothels. Unlike usual infanticide&mdash;where historically girls were more likely to be killed at birth&mdash; a brothel site at Ashkelon in Israel revealed that nearly all of the babies were boys.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-14401305 ''Roman dead baby 'brothel' mystery deepens''], BBC</ref>\n\n[[File:1537 Braunschweiger Monogrammist Bordellszene anagoria.JPG|thumb|left|Brothel scene; [[Brunswick Monogrammist]], 1537; [[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin]]]]\nCities first began setting up municipal brothels between 1350 and 1450 CE.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Timeline--Prostitution|url=http://prostitution.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=000117|work=Should prostitution be legal?|publisher=ProCon.org|accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref> Municipalities often owned, operated, and regulated the legal brothels. Governments would set aside certain streets where a keeper could open a brothel.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heckel |first=N.M. |title=Sex, Society, and Medieval Women |url=http://www.lib.rochester.edu/camelot/medsex/text.htm |publisher=River Campus Libraries |accessdate=23 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102214718/http://www.lib.rochester.edu/camelot/medsex/text.htm |archivedate=November 2, 2011 }}</ref> These separate sections of town were the precursors to the so-called \"red light districts\". Not only did the towns restrict where a keeper could open a brothel, but they also put constraints on when the brothel could be open. For example, most brothels were forbidden to be open for business on Sunday and religious holidays. The reason for this is not completely clear. Some scholars believe these restrictions were enforced to make the prostitutes go to church but others argue that it was to keep parishioners in church and out of the brothels. Either way, it was a day of no revenue for the keeper.\n\nAlthough brothels were set up as a sexual outlet for men, not all men were allowed to enter them. Clerics, married men, and Jews were prohibited.{{sfn|Bennett|1989|pp=100\u2013134}} Often, foreigners such as sailors and traders were the main source of revenue. Local men who frequented the brothels mainly consisted of single men; laws restricting the patrons were not always enforced. Government officials or police would periodically do searches of the brothels to cut down on the number of unpermitted customers. However, since the government was so closely related to the church, common punishments were minor. These restrictions were put in place to protect the wives of married men from any sort of infection.\n\n[[File:William Hogarth - A Rake's Progress - Tavern Scene.jpg|right|thumb|The Brothel Scene from ''[[A Rake's Progress]]'' by [[William Hogarth]], 1735]]\nMultiple restrictions were placed on the residents of brothels. One limitation prohibited prostitutes from borrowing money from her brothel keeper. Prostitutes paid high prices to the brothel keeper for the basic necessities of life: room and board, food, clothes, and toiletries. Room and board was often a price set by the local government but the price for everything else could add up to a common woman's entire earnings. Prostitutes were sometimes prohibited from having a special lover. Some regulations put on prostitutes were made to protect their clients. A woman was kicked out if she was found to have a sexually transmitted disease. Also, the prostitutes were not allowed to pull men into the brothel by their clothing, harass them in the street, or detain them over unpaid debts.{{sfn|Karras|1996|pp=32\u201347}} Clothing worn by prostitutes was regulated as well and had to be distinguishable from that of respectable women. In some places, a prostitute had to have a yellow stripe on her clothing while in others red was the differentiating color. Other towns required harlots to don special headdresses or restricted the wardrobe of proper women. All restrictions placed on prostitutes were put in place not only to protect them but nearby citizens as well.\n\nEven with all the regulations placed on legalized brothels and those people associated with the establishments, they were fated to be done away with. Because of a [[syphilis]] epidemic throughout Europe, many brothels were shut down during the end of the Middle Ages.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Brief History of Brothels|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/a-brief-history-of-brothels-523946.html|publisher=The Independent Newspaper|accessdate=23 July 2017|date=21 January 2006}}</ref> This epidemic had been brought on by Spanish and French military pillages after the return of Christopher Columbus from the newly discovered Americas. The church and citizens alike feared that men who frequented brothels would bring the disease home and infect morally upright people.\n\nFrom the 12th century, brothels in London were located in a district known as the [[Liberty of the Clink]]. This area was traditionally under the authority of the [[Bishop of Winchester]], not the civil authorities. From 1161, the bishop was granted the power to license prostitutes and brothels in the district. This gave rise to the slang term ''Winchester Goose'' for a prostitute. Women who worked in these brothels were denied Christian burial and buried in the unconsecrated graveyard known as [[Cross Bones]].\n\n[[File:Arnaldo Dell'Ira (1903-1943) Sala d'aspetto per la casa di M.me B.,1939.jpg|right|thumb|Interior of a luxurious brothel: \"Waiting room in the house of M.me B.\", project by Italian architect [[Arnaldo dell'Ira]], Rome, 1939.]]\n[[File:Interior of a brothel in Naples, Italy 1945 (1) - Five prostitutes waiting for customers.jpg|right|thumb|Interior of a brothel in [[Naples]], Italy, 1945]]\n\nBy the 16th century, the area was also home to many theatres, (including the [[Globe Theatre]], associated with [[William Shakespeare]]), but brothels continued to thrive. A famous London brothel of the time was ''Holland's Leaguer''. Patrons supposedly included [[James I of England]] and his favourite, [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham]]. It was located in a street that still bears its name{{sfn|Walford|1878|pp=29-44}} and also inspired the 1631 play, ''[[Holland's Leaguer (play)|Holland's Leaguer]]''. [[Charles I of England]] licensed a number of brothels including the [[Silver Cross Tavern]] in London, which retains its licence to modern day because it was never revoked.\n\nThe authorities of Medieval Paris followed the same path as those in London and attempted to confine prostitution to a particular district. [[Louis IX of France|Louis IX]] (1226\u20131270) designated nine streets in the [[Beaubourg]] [[Historical quarters of Paris|Quartier]] where it would be permitted. In the early part of the 19th century, state-controlled legal brothels (then known as \"''maisons de tol\u00e9rance''\" or \"''maisons closes''\") started to appear in several French cities. By law, they had to be run by a woman (typically a former prostitute) and their external appearance had to be discreet. The ''maisons'' were required to light a red lantern when they were open (from which is derived the term [[red-light district]]) and the prostitutes were only permitted to leave the ''maisons'' on certain days and only if accompanied by its head. By 1810, Paris alone had 180 officially approved brothels.\n\nDuring the first half of the 20th century, some Paris brothels, such as [[le Chabanais]] and [[le Sphinx]], were internationally known for the luxury they provided. The French government sometimes included a visit to the ''Chabanais'' as part of the program for foreign guests of state, disguising it as a ''visit with the President of the Senate'' in the official program.<ref name=sz>Die Sphinx im Freudenhaus, ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]'', 17 August 1996. {{in lang|de}}</ref> The ''Hotel Marigny'', established in 1917 in the [[2nd arrondissement of Paris]], was one of several that were well known for catering to gay male clients.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sin city: show celebrates the Paris brothel that was loved by Cary Grant |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/sin-city-show-celebrates-the-paris-brothel-that-was-loved-by-cary-grant-1815759.html |newspaper=The Independent |date= 6 November 2009|accessdate=30 January 2011 |first=Genevieve |last=Roberts}}</ref> Premises suspected of being gay brothels, including the Hotel Marigny, were however subject to frequent police raids,{{sfn|Jackson|2009|p=29}} perhaps indicating less tolerance for them from the authorities.\n\nIn most European countries, brothels were made illegal after World War II. France outlawed brothels in 1946, after a campaign by [[Marthe Richard]]. The backlash against them was in part due to their wartime collaboration with the Germans during the [[German occupation of France during World War II|occupation of France]]. Twenty-two Paris brothels had been commandeered by the Germans for their exclusive use; some had made a great deal of money by catering for German officers and soldiers.<ref name=daily>Peter Allen, [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-1175836/Sleeping-enemy-How-horizontal-collaborators-Paris-brothels-enjoyed-golden-age-entertaining-Hitlers-troops.html Sleeping with the enemy: How 'horizontal collaborators' in Paris brothels enjoyed a golden age entertaining Hitler's troops], ''Daily Mail'', 1 May 2009</ref> One brothel in the [[Monmartre]] District of the French capital was part of an escape network for [[prisoner of war|POW]]s and downed airmen.{{sfn|Regan|1992|p=37}}\n\nItaly made brothels illegal in 1959. The 2010s decade has seen the introduction of sex dolls and sexbots on the premises of some brothels.{{sfn|Levy|2007|pp=833-858}}\n\n===East Asia===\nBrothels have been used formally in [[China]] for prostitution and [[entertainment]] since [[Ancient China]] in its [[feudal]] period. For much of China's ancient and imperial history, brothels were owned by wealthy [[merchants]], typically stereotyped as \"madams\", and engaged in business in urban areas such as the Capital city. Prostitutes, or \"[[courtesans]]\" as they were known, were well-dressed and groomed to the proper table and drinking [[manners]](\u79ae). A Chinese prostitute may have been artistic and skilled at practices such as [[dancing]], playing [[musical instruments]], [[singing]] and conversing in [[verse (poetry)|verse]]. Prostitution was not [[outlawed]] in ancient and imperial China (although prostitutes were not considered fit for marriage to men of respectable social ranking) and instead prostitutes hosted in street brothels were popularly placed in the same [[social class]] as female [[artisans]] and regarded as elegant, albeit tainted, beings, most notably courtesans who used similar means to entertain members of [[nobility]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinawhisper.com/top-10-famous-prostitutes-in-chinese-history/|title=The 8 Famous Prostitutes in Chinese History|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref> Both young women and men worked as prostitutes in these elaborate brothel settings, though historical records and works of [[literature]] have widely [[Romanticism|romanticized]] the free-flowing, artistic nature of female prostitutes.\n\nThe practice of hosting prostitutes in these elaborate brothels spread to surrounding regions of [[Chinese culture sphere|Chinese cultural influence]], notably in [[Japan]] after the sixth century [[AD]], where prostitutes and courtesans evolved to develop the ''[[Oiran]]'' and ''[[Geisha]]'' entertainment professions. Again, the ''geisha'' of Japan emphasized good table manners, artistic skills, elegant styling and sophisticated, tactical conversational skills. The practice also spread to [[Korea]], where prostitutes evolved into the [[Korean people|Korean]] ''[[kisaeng]]''.\n\n===India===\nThe governments of many Indian [[princely state]]s had regulated [[prostitution in India]] prior to the 1860s. The [[British Raj]] enacted the [[Prostitution in colonial India#Cantonment Act of 1864|Cantonment Act of 1864]] to regulate [[prostitution in colonial India]] as a matter of accepting a necessary evil so that the British soldiers could seek sexual gratification when away from their homes.<ref name=tambe2005>{{cite journal|last=Tambe|first=Ashwini|title=The Elusive Ingenue:A transnational Feminist Analysis of European Prostitution in Colonial Bombay|journal=Gender and Society|volume=19|issue=2|date=19 February 2005|pages=160\u201379|doi=10.1177/0891243204272781}}</ref> The Cantonment Acts regulated and structured prostitution in the British [[military bases]] which provided for about twelve to fifteen Indian women kept in brothels called ''chaklas'' for each regiment of thousand British [[soldier]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-24530198|title=Horrors of India's brothels documented|date=2013-11-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB}}</ref> They were licensed by military officials and were allowed to consort with soldiers only.<ref name=bhandari2010>{{cite journal|last=Bhandari|first=Sudhanshu|title=Prostitution in Colonial India|url=http://www.mainstreamweekly.net/article2142.html|accessdate=October 13, 2012|journal=Mainstream Weekly|date=June 19, 2010|volume=XLVIII|number=26}}</ref>\n\nBrothels in India came into life in the early 1920s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.escortgirlgurgaon.com/blog/5-interesting-effects-of-poor-market-conditions-on-indian-escort-industry/#Indian-brothels-history|title=5 Interesting Effects of Poor Market Conditions on Indian Escort Industry\u2014LifeSide|website=www.escortgirlgurgaon.com|access-date=2017-07-27|date=2017-07-22}}</ref> when dance groups in [[Maharashtra]] such as ''Lavani'' and dance-drama performance artists, ''called Tamasha'' artists, functioned as prostitutes. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Rege|first=Sharmila|date=2002|title=Conceptualising Popular Culture: 'Lavani' and 'Powada' in Maharashtra|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/4411876|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=37|issue=11|pages=1038\u20131047|issn=0012-9976}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dalitweb.org/?p=2556,%20https://www.dalitweb.org/?p=2556|title=The linked caste slavery of the Kolhatis and the Bedias {{!}} Savari|date=2014-04-28|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Notably, such professions were strongly connected to caste and income levels.<ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> Enormous amounts of money earned made the show's organizers move the show to different parts of India such as [[Lucknow]], [[Jaipur]] and [[Kolkata]], giving birth to the modern brothel industry in India.{{Clarify|reason=statement lacks any information about when, where and how much of the details|date=December 2018}}\n\n===United States===\nFrom 1911 to 1913 the [[United States Department of Justice]] undertook the task of collecting information on the numbers of prostitutes in brothels in order to use this information against the much feared \"[[White slavery (prostitution)|White Slave Traffic]]\".{{sfn|Woolston|1969|p=38}}  This effort collected information from 318 cities of 26 Eastern states. It estimated about 100,000 women to be working in brothels at the time, yet some estimated the total number of prostitutes to be as high as 500,000.{{sfn|Woolston|1969|p=39}}\n\nDuring the late nineteenth century, brothels in the United States were no secret. George Kneeland articulated his growing concern about the organized sex business in America well, saying that prostitution had grown into a \"highly commercialized and profitable business that penetrated the deepest recesses of the political, cultural and economic life of the city.\"{{sfn|Kneeland|Davis|1913| }} Brothels were commonly referred to as \"disorderly houses\", and their residents were called by many names, some [[Euphemism|euphemistic]]\u2014e.g., \"abandoned woman\", \"bawd good-time daisy\", \"fallen angel\", \"fille de joie\", \"jeweled bird\", \"lady of the evening\", \"shady lady\", \"soiled dove\", \"wanton woman\", and \"woman of the town\"\u2014and some less kind\u2014e.g., \"hooker\", \"slut\", and \"whore\".{{sfn|McKell|2009|p=5}} As the 19th century went on, prostitution as a profession became more common, rather than just occasionally necessitated soliciting. As a result of these changes, the way prostitution was practiced changed.{{sfn|Walkoitz|1982| }}  Many prostitutes still practiced their trade independently, but the new class of professional prostitutes created a demand for a location to do their regular business, and the brothel served this purpose.{{sfn|Rosen|1983| }}\n \t\nVisitors could easily find disorderly houses by merely opening up the local or statewide directories, such as the 1895 ''Travelers' Guide of Colorado''.{{sfn|McKell|2009|p=4}} This 66-page manual helped the interested client decide which brothel was right for him. These manuals did not attract by using euphemistic language, and though bold by standards of the time, were not crude. Some examples read: \"Twenty young ladies engaged nightly to entertain guest\", and \"Strangers cordially welcome\".  In some areas, brothels simply could not be ignored. A nineteenth-century authority describes the city of New Orleans as such: \"The extent of licentiousness and prostitution here is truly appalling and doubtless without a parallel in the whole civilized world. The indulgence and practice is so general and common that men seldom seek to cover up their acts or go in disguise.\"{{sfn|Fernando|1963|p=254}}\n\nThe average house held five to twenty working girls; some higher end brothels also employed staff servants, musicians, and a bouncer. The typical brothel contained several bedrooms, all furnished. Some upscale brothels were much larger; such is the case with that owned by Mary Ann Hall of [[Arlington, Virginia]].{{sfn|Webb|2004|p=26}}  It is described as \"a rather grand house with twenty-five rooms and was enclosed by a brick wall. The interior was elegantly furnished. The principle rooms on the first floor contained large oil paintings, Brussels carpets, red plush 'parlor furniture', \u00e9tag\u00e8res (a shelf for small ornaments), and numerous items of silver plate.\"{{sfn|Milner Associates|loc=Appendix II}}  An archeological dig of the area outside of Mary Ann Hall's estate revealed a high quality of material superior to those in surrounding working-class areas.  This included many champagne bottles and corks, wire cages from such bottles, perfume bottles, high-quality porcelain with gilt edging, along with remnants of exotic foods\u2014coconut shells and berry seeds, bones from beef, fish, and pork indicating that elegant meals were being eaten at this high-class brothel.{{sfn|Milner Associates|pp=111\u2013197}}  These \"five and ten dollar parlor houses\" attracted wealthy men, who used the facilities much as a gentlemen's social club,{{sfn|Rosen|1983|p= 86}} where they made business and political connections, met with associates, and had exquisite dinners with wine, champagne, and women. Brothels were not only for the wealthy.  \"One-dollar houses\" were visited by those of the working class. A 1910 Kansas vice report compares the two: \"A few brothels were equipped with expensive furniture and furnishings including the finest of upholstered chairs, well-done paintings and costly rugs, which others were hovels of repulsive squalor.\"{{sfn|Johnson|1911|p=98}}\n\nWomen joined brothels from all walks of life. The average prostitute was approximately 21,{{sfn|McKell|2009|p=6}} but many were as young as 13 or as old as 50. Typically thought of as an escape for young, poor, troubled women, brothels sometimes attracted those less expected. Trained musicians and singers sometimes were lured into it by their interest in easy money and fun times.{{sfn|McKell|2009|p=19}} Some others turned to brothels to get out of their boring, abusive, or otherwise unfulfilling marriages. Although they might be of various classes, ethnicities, and ages, most women who began or joined brothels had a shared goal: quick money.{{sfn|McKell|2009|p=6}} Ironically, many found themselves always indebted to their mistresses. Her lack of credit made a prostitute unable to buy items necessary for her trade herself (powder, cosmetics, perfumes, and \"evening wear\") but was forced to buy them through her madam.{{sfn|McKell|2009|p=8}}\n\nSome madams, often former prostitutes themselves, rose to become independently wealthy. One was Mary Ann Hall of Arlington, Virginia. Clearly attractive and a good businesswoman, Mary Ann purchased a lot and built a brick house. That would be the location of an upscale brothel for another 40 years, sitting right at the foot of Capitol Hill. Her brothel was very lucrative, and Mary Ann was able to buy multiple slaves and even a summer home. She was responsible for the behavior of her prostitutes, which could prove challenging since drug abuse was common. A large focus for madams was keeping their business transactions discreet and staying on the good side of the law, which they did so by contributing money to charitable organizations, schools, and churches.\n\nDespite those efforts, much of the profit still went to legal fines and fees, since prostitution was largely illegal. Timely payment of these fines could guarantee a madam that her business could continue without fear of being shut down, usually. Brothels were expected to pay significantly higher rent than others.{{sfn|Webb|2004|pp=24\u201333}} Another upscale bordello was the Big Brick in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], built and operated by [[Grace Peixotto]], the daughter of the Rev. Solomon Cohen Peixotto, and the madam of the most infamous brothel in the history of the city.{{sfn|Jones|2006|pp=19\u201323}}\n\nA madam stayed involved in her business. Running a house with so many in it required skill. A brothel required the purchase of regular food and food preparation. A madam had to monitor the cleanliness of the brothel, including the sheets, which had to be changed several times in an evening, and a stock of wines and liquors for clientele. She was the boss of the brothel and so a madam fired and hired servants, maids, and prostitutes. New faces in the brothel were desired by patrons and so madams had to find new women to recruit. Sometimes, that meant taking in a less-than-desired woman but one with youth and good looks. The \"new\" prostitute received training, cosmetics, and clothes from the madam. A prostitute from Kansas City is recorded as saying that she is no match for the \"proper\" behavior and dress required for the famous Ice Palace in Chicago.{{sfn|Rosen|1983|p=87}}\n\nDisorderly houses or any other dwelling used for purposes of selling sex or other lewd acts in the early 20th century were illegal with a few exceptions: the states of Arkansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, New Mexico, and South Carolina. Penalties could range from $1,000 and time in jail, to much smaller fines.{{sfn|Rosen|1983| }}\n\n===Military brothels===\n\nUntil recently, in several armies around the world, mobile brothels were attached to the army as auxiliary units, especially attached to combat units on long-term deployments abroad. Because it is a controversial subject, military brothels and the women who provided sex services in them were often designated with creative [[euphemism]]s. Examples of such jargon are {{lang|fr|la bo\u00eete \u00e0 bonbons}} ({{lang-en|\"the sweet box\"}}), replacing the term \"{{lang|fr|[[bordel militaire de campagne]]}}\". [[France]] used mobile brothels during the [[First World War]], the [[Second World War]] and the [[First Indochina War]] to supply sex services to French soldiers who were facing combat in areas where brothels were unusual, such as at the [[front line]] or in isolated garrisons.<ref>World Association of International Studies [http://cgi.stanford.edu/group/wais/cgi-bin/index.php?p=2351 article] retrieved on March 10, 2007 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612081843/http://cgi.stanford.edu/group/wais/cgi-bin/index.php?p=2351 |date=June 12, 2007 }}</ref>{{sfn|Windrow|2004| }} Brothels were outlawed in France in 1946; but the [[French Foreign Legion]] continued to use mobile brothels until the late 1990s.\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], women drawn from throughout the [[Far East]] were forced into [[sexual slavery]] by the occupation armies of [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japan]] in brothels known as [[Ianjo]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://japanfocus.org/products/details/2373 |title=Japan's 'Comfort Women': It's time for the truth |date=March 8, 2007 |accessdate=2008-12-15 |publisher=[[The Asia-Pacific Journal: Japan Focus]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109083324/http://japanfocus.org/products/details/2373 |archivedate=January 9, 2009 }}</ref> These women were referred to as \"[[comfort women]]\" (kanji=\u6170\u5b89\u5a66; hiragana=\u3044\u3042\u3093\u3075). During the Second World War in Europe, [[German military brothels in World War II|Nazi Germany created military brothels]] where an estimated 34,140 enslaved women from Nazi-occupied Europe, particularly [[Poland]], were forced to work as prostitutes in brothels.{{sfn|Herbermann|2000|p=33\u201334}}\n\nAfter the Japanese surrender following the Second World War, the Japanese government formed the [[Recreation and Amusement Association]] and recruited 55,000 of its \"patriotic women\" to \"sacrifice themselves\" to the [[G.I. (military)|G.I.]] occupation, to protect the chastity of pure Japanese womenfolk.<ref name=ny19951027>{{cite news | first=Nicholas | last= Kristof | title=Fearing G.I. Occupiers, Japan Urged Women Into Brothels | date=1995-10-27 | publisher=New York Times | url =https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/27/world/fearing-gi-occupiers-japan-urgesd-women-into-brothels.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm | accessdate = 2013-05-18 }}</ref>\n\nIn South Korea, women who worked as prostitutes for UN forces were called [[Western princess]]es. Between the 1950s and 1960s, 60% of [[Prostitutes in South Korea for the U.S. military|South Korean prostitutes worked near the US military bases]].{{sfnm|1a1=Clough|1a2=Halley|1y=2007|1p=163|2a1=Cho|2y=2008|2p=104}} Korean leader [[Park Chung-hee]] encouraged the [[sex trade]], particularly with the U.S. military, in order to generate revenue.<ref name=IBT20130429>{{cite news | first=Palash | last=Ghosh | title=South Korea: A Thriving Sex Industry In A Powerful, Wealthy Super-State | date=2013-04-29 | publisher=[[International Business Times]] | url =http://www.ibtimes.com/south-korea-thriving-sex-industry-powerful-wealthy-super-state-1222647 | accessdate = 2013-05-18 }}</ref> Since the mid-1990s, [[Filipina]] and [[Russia]]n women have worked as prostitutes for U.S. servicemen in South Korea.<ref name=joong20021019>{{cite news | title=[EDITORIALS]Deliver them from 'hell' | date=2002-10-19 | publisher=[[Joongang Daily]] | url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=1910008 | accessdate=2013-04-08 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613134822/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=1910008 | archivedate=2013-06-13 }}</ref><ref name=Hankyoreh20091201>{{cite news | title=Filipinas forced into prostitution on the rise in S.Korea | date=2009-12-01 | publisher=[[Hankyoreh]] | url =http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_international/390782.html | accessdate = 2013-05-18 }}</ref><ref name=SS20090926>{{cite news | title=Philippine Embassy has 'watch list' of suspect bars in South Korea|first=Jon|last=Rabiroff | date=September 26, 2009 | publisher=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]] | url=http://www.stripes.com/news/philippine-embassy-has-watch-list-of-suspect-bars-in-south-korea-1.95038 | accessdate = 2013-05-18 }}</ref> In 2010, the [[Philippine government]] stopped approving contracts that promoters use to bring Filipinas to South Korea to work near U.S. military bases.<ref name=SS20100618>{{cite news | title=Report on human trafficking cites South Korean juicy bars|first=Jon|last=Rabiroff | date=June 18, 2010 | publisher=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]] | url=http://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/report-on-human-trafficking-cites-south-korean-juicy-bars-1.107610 | accessdate = 2013-05-18 }}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nAu camp d'Arbalou l'Arbi Le B.M.C. Bordel Militaire de Campagne -1922 Edit Legraverand, phot, Mekn\u00e8s.jpg|A [[Bordel militaire de campagne]] in Morocco in the 1920s.\nBundesarchiv Bild 101II-MW-1019-07, Frankreich, Brest, Soldatenbordell.jpg|German soldiers entering a ''Soldatenbordell'' in [[Brest, France]] (1940). The building is a former [[synagogue]].\nChinese girl from one of the Japanese Army's 'comfort battalions'.jpg|A young Chinese woman from one of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]'s \"comfort battalions\" is interviewed by a British Royal Air Force officer in [[Yangon|Rangoon]] after being liberated in August 1945.\nYasuura House.jpg|U.S. servicemen entered [[Recreation and Amusement Association]] during [[Occupation of Japan]].\nRegistration of comfort women.jpg|The registration of [[Western princess]]es in South Korea on September 13, 1961.\n</gallery>\n\n==Sex doll brothel==\nA number of brothels offering only [[sex doll]]s exist in Japan. There is also one in Barcelona, and recently one named [[Bordoll]] opened in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2018/01/13/inside-germanys-first-sex-doll-brothel-7226156/|title=Inside Germany's first sex doll brothel|date=13 January 2018}}</ref> Another was set to open on 8 September 2018 in Toronto, Canada though it was deemed to be contrary to a by-law in the city, forcing its shutdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/asithappens/as-it-happens-tuesday-edition-1.4801669/toronto-councillor-says-new-sex-doll-brothel-breaks-city-bylaws-1.4802092|title=Toronto councillor says new sex doll brothel breaks city bylaws|date=28 August 2018|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Australia has recently seen its first sex doll available for use in a brothel as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pryanarose.com.au/sex-toy-carmen/|title=Sex Toy Carmen|website=Pryana Rose Brisbane Brothel|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref> February 2018 yet another opened in Aarhus, Denmark.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dukkebordel er \u00e5bnet i Aarhus: - Kunderne er helt almindelige m\u00e6nd |url=https://stiften.dk/aarhus/Dukkebordel-er-aabnet-i-Aarhus-Kunderne-er-helt-almindelige-maend/artikel/502415 |website=stiften.dk |accessdate=7 April 2019 |language=da |date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Artemis (brothel)|Artemis]]\n*[[Barbary Coast, San Francisco]]\n*[[Convention for the Suppression of the Traffic in Persons and of the Exploitation of the Prostitution of Others]]\n*[[Gay bathhouse]]\n*[[Lupanar (Pompeii)]]\n*[[Maxim Wien]]\n*[[Pimp]]\n*[[Prostitution]]\n*[[Sex on Premises Venue]]\n*[[Sex worker]]\n*[[Soapland]]\n*[[Spintria]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Bennett |first1=Judith M. |title=Sisters and Workers in the Middle Ages |date=1989 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=9780226042473 |url=https://archive.org/details/sistersworkersin0000benn |url-access=registration |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|first=Janell L |last=Carroll|title=Sexuality Now: Embracing Diversity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cy9-BAAAQBAJ|date=2 January 2015|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-44603-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cho |first1=Grace M. |title=Haunting the Korean Diaspora: Shame, Secrecy, and the Forgotten War |date=2008 |publisher=U of Minnesota Press |isbn=9780816652747 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=VagzEDjnZpcC&pg=PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Clough |first1=Patricia Ticineto |last2=Halley |first2=Jean |title=The Affective Turn: Theorizing the Social |date=2007 |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=978-0822389606 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DEIIYoYEyD8C&pg=PA164#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book|first=Henrique |last=Fernando |title= Prostitution in Europe and the New World|publisher=London, MacGibbon & Kee|date=1963|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Herbermann |first1=Nanda |title=The Blessed Abyss: Inmate #6582 in Ravensbr\u00fcck Concentration Camp for Women |date=2000 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0814329207 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3JM3AdnmE18C&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Jackson |first1=Julian |title=Living in Arcadia: Homosexuality, Politics, and Morality in France from the Liberation to AIDS |date=2009 |publisher=Univ