{"title_page": "Theresa Tam", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dr. Theresa Tam\n| office = [[Chief Public Health Officer of Canada]]\n| appointer = \n| primeminister = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| predecessor = Gregory W. Taylor\n| termstart = June 26, 2017\n| termend =\n| occupation =  Physician\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place = [[Hong Kong]]\n}}\n\n'''Theresa Tam''' (\u8b5a\u548f\u8a69; born 1965) is a Canadian physician and public servant. On June 26, 2017,<ref name=\"WHO\">{{Cite web\n | title        = Dr Theresa Tam, BMBS (UK), FRCPC: Chief Public Health Officer, Public Health Agency of Canada\n | url=http://www.who.int/about/who_reform/emergency-capacities/oversight-committee/theresa-tam/en/ \n | accessdate   = 23 March 2020\n | website = World Health Organization\n | archiveurl   = https://web.archive.org/web/20181124160118/http://www.who.int/about/who_reform/emergency-capacities/oversight-committee/theresa-tam/en/\n | archivedate  = 15 August 2019\n | url-status   = }}</ref> Tam was appointed to the position of [[Chief Public Health Officer of Canada]] and head of the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] (PHAC). Tam acted as Chief Public Health Officer of Canada after the retirement of Gregory Taylor in December 2016 until her formal appointment by Canadian Minister of Health [[Jane Philpott]] in 2017.\n\nTam, a pediatric infectious disease specialist, held a number of leadership positions at PHAC such as Assistant Deputy Minister of the Infectious Disease Prevention and Control Branch.<ref>{{Citation\n | last    = Canadian Press\n | title   = Top doctor: Theresa Tam appointed to head Public Health Agency of Canada\n | newspaper = The Globe and Mail\n | date      = 26 June 2017\n\n | url     = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/top-doctor-theresa-tam-appointed-to-head-public-health-agency-of-canada/article35472115/\n | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170629125414/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/top-doctor-theresa-tam-appointed-to-head-public-health-agency-of-canada/article35472115/\n | archivedate = 29 June 2017\n | url-status  = live \n}}\n</ref> She has played a leadership role in Canada's response to public health emergencies including [[severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS), pandemic influenza [[H1N1]], [[Ebola]]<ref name=\"WHO\"/> and [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. As part of an advertising campaign distributed by the Government of Canada, Tam appeared in a series of TV commercial airing on all Canadian television and radio stations urging personal hygiene and [[social distancing]] to limit the spread of COVID-19, which began on March 23, 2020 until at least the end of April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/feds-launch-ad-campaign-urging-social-distancing-hygiene-during-covid-19-crisis-1.4863845|title=Feds launch ad campaign urging social distancing, hygiene during COVID-19 crisis|publisher=ctvnews.ca|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> She has taken a controversial position on wearing masks, stating that it while face masks can cut down on the spread of the COVID-19 when worn by someone already infected, it does little for healthy individuals, stating that \"putting a mask on an asymptomatic person is not beneficial<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/chris-selley-official-nonsense-on-masks-and-travel-bans-is-killing-ottawas-coronavirus-credibility|title=Chris Selley: Official nonsense on masks, travel bans is killing Ottawa\u2019s COVID-19 credibility {{!}} National Post|last=Comment|first=Full|date=2020-03-31|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6757571/face-mask-coronavirus-canada-effectiveness/|title=Should you wear a face mask? Coronavirus prompts debate over effectiveness|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. However, there is evidence that such measures can slow down the spread of COVID-19 and that countries that are encouraging the public to wear masks are weathering the pandemic better<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capnews.ca/news/masks-covid19|title=Yes, You Should Be Wearing a Mask. Here\u2019s The Evidence.|website=The Capital|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. There is speculation that her public health position is due to the fact that there is a shortage of masks for front-line healthcare workers in Canada and that officials would like to encourage the public to provide healthcare workers with their masks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/chris-selley-official-nonsense-on-masks-and-travel-bans-is-killing-ottawas-coronavirus-credibility|title=Chris Selley: Official nonsense on masks, travel bans is killing Ottawa\u2019s COVID-19 credibility {{!}} National Post|last=Comment|first=Full|date=2020-03-31|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. \n\nTam said the opioid crisis, which cost over 2500 lives in Canada in 2016, could be higher than 3000 in 2017 if the current trend continues. \"This far surpasses the number of motor-vehicle fatalities.\" She said overprescription of opioids contributed to this.<ref>\n{{Citation\n | last        = Tumility\n | first       = Ryan\n | title       = Government allows unnapproved drugs into Canada to combat opioid crisis | newspaper   = Metro News\n | date        = 28 June 2017\n | url-status  = dead \n | url         = http://www.metronews.ca/news/ottawa/2017/06/28/government-allows-unapproved-drugs-for-opioid-crisis.html\n | archive-url =http://web.archive.org/web/20180314055421/http://www.metronews.ca/news/ottawa/2017/06/28/government-allows-unapproved-drugs-for-opioid-crisis.html  \n | archive-date = 18 March 2018\n }}\n</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTam was born in [[Hong Kong]] and grew up in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Citation\n | last         = McBride \n | first        = Jason \n | title        = The Canadian Leading The Fight Against Vaccine Skeptics\n | newspaper    = Chatelaine\n | date         = 23 August 2019\n | url          = https://www.chatelaine.com/living/ms-chatelaine/theresa-tam-profile/amp/\n | archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200127084034/https://www.chatelaine.com/living/ms-chatelaine/theresa-tam-profile/amp/ \n | archive-date = 27 January 2020 \n | access-date  = 23 March 2020\n\n | url-status   = live }}</ref> She obtained her medical degree at the [[University of Nottingham]], residency at the [[University of Alberta]] and fellowship at [[University of British Columbia]].<ref>{{cite web\n | title       = Chief Public Health Officer of Canada \u2013 Biography   \n | url         = https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/corporate/organizational-structure/canada-chief-public-health-officer/biography.html\n | website     = Government of Canada\n | date        = 20 March 2019 \n | access-date = 23 March 2020\n | url-status  = live \n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323173719/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/corporate/organizational-structure/canada-chief-public-health-officer/biography.html \n | archivedate = 23 March 2020 \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{CanChiefHealthOfficers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tam, Theresa}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian pediatricians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hong Kong descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian health officials]]\n[[Category:Canadian public health doctors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dr. Theresa Tam\n| office = [[Chief Public Health Officer of Canada]]\n| appointer = \n| primeminister = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| predecessor = Gregory W. Taylor\n| termstart = June 26, 2017\n| termend =\n| occupation =  Physician\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place = [[Hong Kong]]\n}}\n\n'''Theresa Tam''' (\u8b5a\u548f\u8a69; born 1965) is a Canadian physician and public servant. On June 26, 2017,<ref name=\"WHO\">{{Cite web\n | title        = Dr Theresa Tam, BMBS (UK), FRCPC: Chief Public Health Officer, Public Health Agency of Canada\n | url=http://www.who.int/about/who_reform/emergency-capacities/oversight-committee/theresa-tam/en/ \n | accessdate   = 23 March 2020\n | website = World Health Organization\n | archiveurl   = https://web.archive.org/web/20181124160118/http://www.who.int/about/who_reform/emergency-capacities/oversight-committee/theresa-tam/en/\n | archivedate  = 15 August 2019\n | url-status   = }}</ref> Tam was appointed to the position of [[Chief Public Health Officer of Canada]] and head of the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] (PHAC). Tam acted as Chief Public Health Officer of Canada after the retirement of Gregory Taylor in December 2016 until her formal appointment by Canadian Minister of Health [[Jane Philpott]] in 2017.\n\nTam, a pediatric infectious disease specialist, held a number of leadership positions at PHAC such as Assistant Deputy Minister of the Infectious Disease Prevention and Control Branch.<ref>{{Citation\n | last    = Canadian Press\n | title   = Top doctor: Theresa Tam appointed to head Public Health Agency of Canada\n | newspaper = The Globe and Mail\n | date      = 26 June 2017\n\n | url     = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/top-doctor-theresa-tam-appointed-to-head-public-health-agency-of-canada/article35472115/\n | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170629125414/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/top-doctor-theresa-tam-appointed-to-head-public-health-agency-of-canada/article35472115/\n | archivedate = 29 June 2017\n | url-status  = live \n}}\n</ref> She has played a leadership role in Canada's response to public health emergencies including [[severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS), pandemic influenza [[H1N1]], [[Ebola]]<ref name=\"WHO\"/> and [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. As part of an advertising campaign distributed by the Government of Canada, Tam appeared in a series of TV commercial airing on all Canadian television and radio stations urging personal hygiene and [[social distancing]] to limit the spread of COVID-19, which began on March 23, 2020 until at least the end of April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/feds-launch-ad-campaign-urging-social-distancing-hygiene-during-covid-19-crisis-1.4863845|title=Feds launch ad campaign urging social distancing, hygiene during COVID-19 crisis|publisher=ctvnews.ca|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> She has taken a controversial position on wearing masks, stating that it while face masks can cut down on the spread of the COVID-19 when worn by someone already infected, it does little for healthy individuals, stating that \"putting a mask on an asymptomatic person is not beneficial<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/chris-selley-official-nonsense-on-masks-and-travel-bans-is-killing-ottawas-coronavirus-credibility|title=Chris Selley: Official nonsense on masks, travel bans is killing Ottawa\u2019s COVID-19 credibility {{!}} National Post|last=Comment|first=Full|date=2020-03-31|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6757571/face-mask-coronavirus-canada-effectiveness/|title=Should you wear a face mask? Coronavirus prompts debate over effectiveness|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. However, there is evidence that such measures can slow down the spread of COVID-19 and that countries that are encouraging the public to wear masks are weathering the pandemic better<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capnews.ca/news/masks-covid19|title=Yes, You Should Be Wearing a Mask. Here\u2019s The Evidence.|website=The Capital|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. There is speculation that her public health position is due the the fact that there is a shortage of masks for front-line healthcare workers in Canada and that officials would like to encourage the public to provide healthcare workers with their masks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/chris-selley-official-nonsense-on-masks-and-travel-bans-is-killing-ottawas-coronavirus-credibility|title=Chris Selley: Official nonsense on masks, travel bans is killing Ottawa\u2019s COVID-19 credibility {{!}} National Post|last=Comment|first=Full|date=2020-03-31|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. \n\nTam said the opioid crisis, which cost over 2500 lives in Canada in 2016, could be higher than 3000 in 2017 if the current trend continues. \"This far surpasses the number of motor-vehicle fatalities.\" She said overprescription of opioids contributed to this.<ref>\n{{Citation\n | last        = Tumility\n | first       = Ryan\n | title       = Government allows unnapproved drugs into Canada to combat opioid crisis | newspaper   = Metro News\n | date        = 28 June 2017\n | url-status  = dead \n | url         = http://www.metronews.ca/news/ottawa/2017/06/28/government-allows-unapproved-drugs-for-opioid-crisis.html\n | archive-url =http://web.archive.org/web/20180314055421/http://www.metronews.ca/news/ottawa/2017/06/28/government-allows-unapproved-drugs-for-opioid-crisis.html  \n | archive-date = 18 March 2018\n }}\n</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTam was born in [[Hong Kong]] and grew up in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Citation\n | last         = McBride \n | first        = Jason \n | title        = The Canadian Leading The Fight Against Vaccine Skeptics\n | newspaper    = Chatelaine\n | date         = 23 August 2019\n | url          = https://www.chatelaine.com/living/ms-chatelaine/theresa-tam-profile/amp/\n | archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200127084034/https://www.chatelaine.com/living/ms-chatelaine/theresa-tam-profile/amp/ \n | archive-date = 27 January 2020 \n | access-date  = 23 March 2020\n\n | url-status   = live }}</ref> She obtained her medical degree at the [[University of Nottingham]], residency at the [[University of Alberta]] and fellowship at [[University of British Columbia]].<ref>{{cite web\n | title       = Chief Public Health Officer of Canada \u2013 Biography   \n | url         = https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/corporate/organizational-structure/canada-chief-public-health-officer/biography.html\n | website     = Government of Canada\n | date        = 20 March 2019 \n | access-date = 23 March 2020\n | url-status  = live \n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323173719/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/corporate/organizational-structure/canada-chief-public-health-officer/biography.html \n | archivedate = 23 March 2020 \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{CanChiefHealthOfficers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tam, Theresa}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian pediatricians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hong Kong descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian health officials]]\n[[Category:Canadian public health doctors]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word reworded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theresa_Tam"}
{"title_page": "My Oh My (Camila Cabello song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by Camila Cabello featuring DaBaby}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Oh My\n| cover      = Camila Cabello - My Oh My.jpg\n| alt        = Image of Camila Cabello wearing a black outfit and DaBaby wearing a fedora positioned at the top of the poster. Underneath is the words 'My Oh My' written in capital letters, as well as a collage of events that occur throughout the music video; Cabello dancing with a partner on the bottom-left corner, a car on the bottom-right corner, Cabello dressed as a femme fatale alongside a group of men wearing suits on the top-right corner, and a group of cowboys on the top-left corner.\n| caption    = Poster of the music video\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Camila Cabello]] featuring [[DaBaby]]\n| album      = [[Romance (Camila Cabello album)|Romance]]\n| released   = January 6, 2020\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| genre      =\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"nme\"/>\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"OCC\"/>\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=51}}\n| label      =\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* [[Syco Music|Syco]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Camila Cabello]]\n* [[DaBaby|Jonathan Kirk]]\n* [[Louis Bell]]\n* [[Frank Dukes|Adam Feeney]]\n* [[Savan Kotecha]]\n* [[Ant Clemons|Anthony Clemons Jr.]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Frank Dukes]]\n* Louis Bell {{small|({{abbr|misc.|miscellaneous producer}})}}\n| chronology = [[Camila Cabello]]\n| prev_title = [[Living Proof (Camila Cabello song)|Living Proof]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[DaBaby]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Suboxone\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title      = My Oh My\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title = [[Shut Up (DaBaby song)|Shut Up]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n{{External music video|1={{YouTube|6fd2kkLmSDQ|\"My Oh My\"}}|header=Music video}}\n}}\n\n\"'''My Oh My'''\" is a song by Cuban-American singer [[Camila Cabello]] featuring vocals from American rapper [[DaBaby]]. The song was released to [[Adult contemporary music|hot adult contemporary radio]] stations in the United States on January 6, 2020 as the fourth single from Cabello's second studio album ''[[Romance (Camila Cabello album)|Romance]]'' (2019). A music video of the song was published to Cabello's [[YouTube]] channel on February 12, 2020. It was written by Cabello, DaBaby, [[Louis Bell]], [[Frank Dukes]], [[Savan Kotecha]] and [[Ant Clemons]], and produced by Dukes and Bell.\n\nCommercially, \"My Oh My\" has reached the top twenty in Australia, Belgium, Canada, Estonia, Greece, Finland, Greece, Hungary, Ireland, Malaysia, New Zealand, Singapore and the United Kingdom. It has also peaked at number 18 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song received Gold certifications in Australia and New Zealand. It was certified Silver in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Background and composition==\nThe recording process for [[Camila Cabello]]'s second studio album ''Romance'' took under ten months, and concluded in October 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=Camila_Cabello|number=1064294149971685376|title=MAKING NEW STUFF AND THINGS!!!|date=November 18, 2018|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter\">{{cite tweet|user=Camila_Cabello|number=1189795610695630848|title=Romance is officially done.|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref> The song was confirmed on November 27, 2019, as the digital only track on the album.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nMusically, \"My Oh My\" is a two minute and fifty one second [[reggaeton]]-influenced [[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/camila-cabello-romance-album-review-2584469|title=Camila Cabello - 'Romance' album review|date=December 6, 2019|website=[[NME]]|accessdate=December 11, 2019|quote='My Oh My', a collab with rapper DaBaby, sees Cabello shedding her good girl image for a roaring cut of sexy, reggaeton-inflected pop}}</ref> and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"OCC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/camila-cabellos-new-album-romance-first-listen-preview__27829/|title=Camila Cabello's new album Romance: First listen preview|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> song which comprises a [[Pop rap|pop-rap]] beat.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cmalone/2019/12/06/camila-cabello-ruminates-on-romance-on-her-sophomore-album/|title=Camila Cabello Ruminates On 'Romance' On Her Sophomore Album|last=Malone|first=Chris|date=December 11, 2019|website=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=December 11, 2019|quote=the song's hybrid pop-rap beat}}</ref> In terms of [[Musical notation|music notation]], \"My Oh My\" was composed using [[Time signature|{{Time signature|4|4}} common time]] in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[C minor]], with a moderate tempo of 104 [[Tempo|beats per minute]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0206017|title=Camila Cabello \"My Oh My\" featuring DaBaby Sheet Music in C Minor|website=Musicnotes.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> The song follows the chord progression of Cm\u2013A{{music|flat}}\u2013G.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cabello's vocal range spans from the low note G<sub>3</sub> to the high note of F<sub>5</sub>, giving the song one octave and six notes of range.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing the release of the parent album, \"My Oh My\" debuted at number 82 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart as an album track due to strong digital downloads. The song climbed to number 61 in its second week, and has since reached a peak of number 18, becoming the second highest-charting single from the album thus far, surpassing \"[[Liar (Camila Cabello song)|Liar]]\" which reached number 52, and behind \"[[Se\u00f1orita (Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello song)|Se\u00f1orita]]\" alongside [[Shawn Mendes]], which reached number one in August.  The track has also debuted at number 35 on the [[Mainstream Top 40]] airplay chart, and has so far peaked at number 9.\n\nInternationally, \"My Oh My\" reached the top ten in Ireland, where it peaked at number six, while charting within the top twenty in various other countries including Australia, Belgium, Finland, Greece, the Netherlands, New Zealand, and Singapore. In the United Kingdom, the track reached number 13, earning Cabello her eighth top 20 single there.\n\n===TikTok dance===\nAccording to ''[[Forbes]]'', this song was especially notable for its ability to leverage the popularity of the short musical video app [[TikTok]] and the user-created dance that boosted the song to become a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/monicamercuri/2019/12/23/how-tiktok-influenced-music-discovery-in-2019/|title=How TikTok Influenced Music Discovery In 2019|date=December 13, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nOn February 12, 2020, the music video for the song was released at 3pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] on [[YouTube]], as an old fashioned, Golden-age Hollywood, black-and-white style video directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8550242/camila-cabello-my-oh-my-video-announcemont|title=Can You Guess the Plot of Camila Cabello's Upcoming 'My Oh My' Video?|last=Aniftos|first=Raina|date=February 5, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> Cabello stars as an actress who's tired of always starring as a [[Damsel in distress|helpless character]] and wishes to \"be the hero\". She then goes to a bar and meets an up-and-coming movie director, portrayed by [[DaBaby]], who then hires her to play the role she always wanted. Throughout the video, Cabello utilizes a sword in a ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1|Kill Bill]]'' inspired film titled 'La Bonita Blade',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8550857/camila-cabello-my-oh-my-video-dababy|title=Camila Cabello Makes Her Mark on Hollywood With DaBaby for 'My Oh My' Video|last=Saponara|first=Michael|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref> and performs a ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''-style dance, alongside the use of subtitles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3156429/camila-cabello-my-oh-my-video-dababy/|title=Camila Cabello Is Not That Innocent In Her Cinematic 'My Oh My' Video|last=Roth|first=Madeline|website=[[MTV News]]|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Lyric video===\nOn January 10, 2020, a lyric video for the song was released on YouTube, done in a Golden age of American animation style. As of February 2020, the lyric video has surpassed 11 million views on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|title=Camila Cabello - My Oh My (Lyric Video) ft. DaBaby|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nQNynY4A5m4|via=[[YouTube]]|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nCabello and DaBaby performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' on December 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8546236/camila-cabello-dababy-my-oh-my-tonight-show|title=Camila Cabello & DaBaby Hit the Quad for Flirty, School Daze 'My Oh My' on 'Tonight Show': Watch|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> On March 5, 2020 Cabello performed a solo version of the song at the [[2020 Global Awards]]. On March 29, Cabello performed an acustic version of the song for [[Elton John]]'s [[iHeart Living Room Concert for America]], with [[Shawn Mendes]] playing the acoustic guitar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9345919/camila-cabello-shawn-mendes-my-oh-my-concert-for-america|title=Camila Cabello & Shawn Mendes Strip Down 'My Oh My' for iHeart Living Room Concert for America|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n==Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/124277249|title=Romance / Camila Cabello|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n* [[Camila Cabello]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting\n* [[DaBaby]] \u2013 featured vocals, songwriting\n* [[Frank Dukes]] \u2013 production, songwriting\n* [[Louis Bell]] \u2013 miscellaneous production, songwriting, [[Audio engineer|recording]]\n* [[Ant Clemons|Anthony Clemons Jr.]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Savan Kotecha]] \u2013 songwriting\n* Chris Galland \u2013 [[Audio mixing|mixing]]\n* [[Manny Marroquin]] \u2013 mixing\n* Brian Taylor \u2013 [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|19|artist=Camila Cabello feat. DaBaby|song=My Oh My|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|38|artist=Camila Cabello feat. DaBaby|song=My Oh My|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|31|artist=Camila Cabello feat. DaBaby|song=My Oh My|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|6|artist=Camila Cabello feat. DaBaby|song=My Oh My|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Bolivia ([[Monitor Latino]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charts.monitorlatino.com/top20/Print/Bolivia/general/20200316|title=Bolivia General|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 21, 2020|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200321173948/http://charts.monitorlatino.com/top20/Print/Bolivia/general/20200316|archivedate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| 14\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|13|artist=Camila Cabello|rowheader=true|ac